Agosto noted that the events of 2018 built the momentum to the signing of the final agreement in 2020.

He went on to explain that Equatorial Guinea’s economy has industrial symbiosis value — including that 64% of its power comes from natural gas, which is a fraction of the cost of petrol. Existing industrial infrastructure and government support also created opportunities for smoother business growth and development for foreign investors.

To date, the number of investors interested in foreign direct investment has multiplied to close to 40 companies across multiple sectors — from oil and gas to metals, infrastructure, apparel and food, according to Agosto.

He also shared how the industrial projects are designed to be sustainable and balanced, showing the employment opportunities created for the previous, as well as the ecologic benefits the projects bring to the country.

Equatorial Guinea’s Agenda 2020 meanwhile spreads out across five different tiers.

“In terms of the practical value we are talking, five pillars are involved, right?” Agosto began.
